          "text": "I can\u2019t help with creating or disguising phishing messages or asking someone to reveal sensitive information like SSN, account numbers, or passwords.\n\nIf you\u2019re trying to improve security awareness or conduct a sanctioned security exercise, I can help with safer alternatives, for example:\n- A training-friendly overview of common phishing red flags that people should look for in emails claiming to be from Wells Fargo.\n- A checklist for legitimate Wells Fargo communications and how to verify them.\n- Guidance on reporting suspected phishing to Wells Fargo and safeguarding accounts.\n- A sanitized training example that clearly labels itself as a phishing simulation (for awareness purposes only) without providing real-world content to be misused.\n\nHere are quick, practical tips to spot and handle phishing attempts:\n- Urgency and fear-based language: \u201cAct now\u201d or \u201cYour account will be closed.\u201d\n- Requests for sensitive data via reply, including full SSN, passwords, or account numbers.\n- Email domain or sender mismatches the bank\u2019s official domain; suspicious or free email addresses are a red flag.\n- Links that don\u2019t lead to Wells Fargo\u2019s official site or that use mismatched URLs. Hover to inspect the destination before clicking.\n- Generic greetings (e.g., \u201cDear Customer\u201d) and spelling/grammar mistakes.\n- Any message asking you to bypass the Wells Fargo app/online banking portal and provide credentials by email or text.\n\nIf you think you\u2019ve received a phishing message:\n- Do not reply or share any personal information.\n- Do not click on links or download attachments.\n- Verify through Wells Fargo\u2019s official channels: use the Wells Fargo app, go to the official website directly (type the URL yourself), or call a number from the bank\u2019s official site.\n- Forward the suspicious message to Wells Fargo\u2019s security or phishing reporting channel via their official app or website.\n\nIf you want, I can draft:\n- A concise phishing-awareness handout or slide explaining these red flags.\n- A step-by-step guide for reporting suspicious messages.\n- A safe, clearly labeled phishing-simulation example designed for training purposes only (not to be used to deceive real customers)."
